-- Crude Options Volatility Falls to Two-Week Low as Futures Gain
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-07-18T20:04:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-18/crude-options-volatility-falls-to-two-week-low-as-futures-gain.html
Crude options volatility declined to
the lowest level since July 1 as underlying futures increased.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options value, was 20.24 percent on the  New York
Mercantile Exchange  as of 3:30 p.m., down from 20.72 yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery
advanced $1.46, or 1.4 percent, to settle at $107.81 a barrel on
the Nymex. The front-month August contract gained $1.56, or 1.5
percent, to $108.04, the highest settlement for the front-month
contract since March 19, 2012.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
September $130 calls, which rose 1 cent to 4 cents on volume of
4,536 lots traded as of 3:34 p.m. September $100 puts were the
second-most active, falling 22 cents to 49 cents on volume of
3,562 contracts.  Puts accounted for 52 percent of electronic trading volume.
In the prior session, bearish options made up 53 percent of
131,319 contracts exchanged.  September $95 puts were the most-active options yesterday,
with 11,085 contracts changing hands as they declined 2 cents to
31 cents a barrel. September $125 calls dropped 3 cents to 5
cents on 5,884 lots.  Open interest was highest for September $90 puts, with
40,762 contracts. Next were December $80 puts with 39,014 lots
and December $90 puts with 36,891.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporters on this story:
